My indeed first negative experience ordering from Seamless. Part of the order was missing. Guy who packed it was trying to convince me over the phone that he checked it couple of times - this haven't changed the fact of missing items.  One of the items was just replaced by what they had available. I was promised to get a credit within 24 hours. It haven't happened. Called seamless who said their policy won't allow them to change anything after 24 hours - I guess guy at Taheni knew it.  Called the store again, Enis told me to email receipt with details so they can process a refund of missing items.  Two days later nothing had happened again. Asked for Enis (sure it was him who picked my call) and was told that Enis doesn't work there any longer, but they will look in the emails and fix the issue.  Still not resolved... Great customer service.....  And if you get a salad - half of the portion is toasted bread - which is not listed anywhere.

I walked into Taheni, because quite frankly not much was open late on a holiday. Seeing it was a quick-service restaurant, my expectation were low. You order via the self-serve kiosk, and see images of the food, but not the food itself. I ordered falafel on a bed of salad with teheni sauce, and added halloumi for an extra few. It’s seemed like an easy choice, but honestly, wow. The was a treat, and the falafel was the freshest I’d ever eaten. It was soft, which is often not the case, and not overly fried either. I was surprised by how much I enjoyed it. The place is clean, and the staff were nice, even working a holiday. Would return, and would give it six stars if I could.

They have a mix of old salads which means it’s not fresh or as fresh. Half my bowl was old leaves with the brown decaying edges. The falafel was delicious. I think my favorite was the hummus and pita.  Service: oddly the entire place only needs a cook. You order at a Seamless kiosk computer. I wish they’d have better visuals since we really had no idea what type of salad we were ordering. I was expecting a salad, didn’t know it was a Mediterranean  salad considering there’s also an option to order a Mediterranean salad.  Atmosphere: it’s nice and simple. We ordered the lamb platter that came with hummus and lamb shawarma on top, a side of falafel, and a tamarind drink. Everything came out to about $21 and change.  The hummus and falafel were both good but they did not have pita and gave us a laffa/flatbread instead, which was disappointing because you think they'd let you know before you placed the order if they didn't have one of the main items of your order.  I was also very disappointed by the lamb shawarma - it was grilled as opposed to being shaved off a roasting spit. The lamb also seemed like it wasn't flavored very well, much less have any shawarma flavor at all. It tasted more like a grilled lamb than lamb shawarma.  The tamarind drink was interesting, but they forgot our drink and we had to remind them for it.  Overall, I don't think I'd come back.

Taheni has what may be the best falafel I've ever had, here in New York or anywhere else. I don't think anyone makes it with the same thin, delicately fried outer layer and intensely soft inner. I bought the platter for $10.95, which included mujadara, a salad, hummus and pita (all of which were serviceable), and 5 balls of that phenomenal falafel. I left feeling incredible.

no longer free delivery.  boo hoo....  Seriously, why are customers allowing these delivery services to muscle in and force owners to use them.  Free delivery used to be a  NYC institution.  Esp for schwarma shops, asian delivery, etc.  Cheap good meals in the neighborhood.  People should boycott these services.  New digitally enabled businesses like Uber or Amazon, etc made things cheaper and more convenient.   Seemless, Grubhub, etc have just raised prices.  Yelp games their reviews and pushes people to their own delivery service.  Why patronize???
